@tqchen suppose we have
sum(x) = if (x == 0) {0} else {x + sum(x - 1)}
if we try to use the LCA scope, we will lift the 'x + sum(x - 1)' out of the if else, and in the same scope as the parent if, which is incorrect and make the whole thing an infinite loop. It is one reason the definition is complex.

@MarisaKirisame  in your particular case

```
 if (x == 0) {
    0
 } else {
   %1 = x + sum(x - 1)
   %1
}
```
Because %1 is only used in the scope of else, all its usage is only in the scope of else. So the LCA of %1 is the else scope. However, if the code is:

```
%1 = %x -1
 if (%1 == 0) {
    0
 } else {
   %2 = x + sum(%1)
   %1
}
```
Then because ``%1`` get used in both the condition of if, and else scope of if, its LCA is outside the if scope.
